I&#39;m not sure what you mean by &quot;popping open the cans&quot;.  From what
you&#39;ve described, I think I&#39;d be tempted to write some kind of
paramaterized test case that takes in several potential cases, like:

public static Test suite {
  TestSuite suite = new TestSuite(...);
  suite.addTest(
        new MailerTest(&quot;&lt;Kevin Klinemeier&gt; zipwow@...&quot;,
                            new
InternetAddress(&quot;zipwow@...&quot;,&quot;Kevin Klinemeier&quot;,&quot;UTF-8&quot;));
  suite.addTest(
        new MailerTest(&quot;zipwow@...&quot;,
                            new InternetAddress(&quot;zipwow@...&quot;,&quot;&quot;,&quot;UTF-8&quot;));
  return suite;
}

public MailerTest(String testAddress, InternetAddress expectedResult) {...}

public void runTest() {
   MailSender mailSender = new MailSender();
    InternetAddress result = mailSender.setAddress(testAddress);
    assertEquals(&quot;Wrong result for [&quot;+testAddress+&quot;]&quot;,expectedResult,result);
}

Your method takes a collection and not individual addresses, but you
get the idea.  Ultimately pretty simple code, if you&#39;re familiar with
the paramaterized test case approach.


