&gt; On Wed, 26 Jan 2005 16:18:30 -0800, Kevin Klinemeier &lt;zipwow@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; Simple, snide answer:  Test your expectations of the results.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; You mention that the method in question makes some validations.  After
&gt; &gt; calling the setter, make your assertions about the exceptions, error
&gt; &gt; codes, or whatever it is you&#39;re returning if the validation fails.
&gt; &gt; You may have known that part already.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; So how do you test the objects created when validation passes?  You&#39;ve
&gt; &gt; got black-box and white-box approaches.  I prefer black-box as a first
&gt; &gt; try, but that&#39;s mostly because I write the tests first, so the code is
&gt; &gt; really more of an empty box :P
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; To do this black-box-style, look to the other access points to your
&gt; &gt; class.  You mention that the private collection is full of
&gt; &gt; InternetAddress objects.  Does your class communicate these to a mail
&gt; &gt; broker object?  Can you pass in a mock implementation of that object
&gt; &gt; that records what it&#39;s been told?  Here&#39;s a pseudocode example:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; MockCommunicationsBroker broker = new MockCommunicationsBroker();
&gt; &gt; MailSender mailSender = new MailSender(broker); //class under test --
&gt; &gt; given the mock broker
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Collection goodValues = getGoodValues();//however you get your test data
&gt; &gt; mailSender.setRecipients(goodValues);
&gt; &gt; mailSender.send();  //presumably interacts with the broker
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Collection generatedRecipients = broker.getRecipients();
&gt; &gt; assertEquals(&quot;Wrong recipients&quot;,expectedValues,generatedRecipients);
&gt; &gt; //hand converted expected values that match the input to the setter
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; A white-box approach would be to make your private collection
&gt; &gt; protected or use reflection and a lax security profile to &quot;reach
&gt; &gt; inside&quot; and access them directly.  Not as useful for refactoring, and
&gt; &gt; a little less &quot;pure&quot;, but easier to implement.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; -Kevin
